<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Quel.; Mem. Soc. Emul. Montbeliard, Ser. 2, 5: 128" authorityYear="1872" baseAuthorityName="Pers." class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma mesophaeum" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="mesophaeum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma mesophaeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed, but apparently uncommon in Greenland with only 11 records (2.9%). This is in contrast to the frequency in Europe, where it is very common and widely distributed (
<bibRefCitation author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
). From alpine and arctic Europe, it is known from the Alps, Southern Carpathians, Svalbard and Iceland. Outside Europe and Greenland, there are a few records from the Rocky Mountains (Colorado, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" author="Cripps, C" journalOrPublisher="MycoKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 54" refId="B9" refString="Cripps, C, Eberhardt, U, Schuetz, N, Beker, HJ, Evenson, VS, Horak, E, 2019. The genus Hebeloma in the Rocky Mountain alpine zone. MycoKeys 46: 1 - 54, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" title="The genus Hebeloma in the Rocky Mountain alpine zone." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" volume="46" year="2019">Cripps et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
) and arctic Canada (
<bibRefCitation author="Ohenoja, E" journalOrPublisher="North American Fungi" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="85 - 96" refId="B38" refString="Ohenoja, E, Ohenoja, M, 2010. Larger fungi of the Canadian Arctic. North American Fungi 5: 85 - 96" title="Larger fungi of the Canadian Arctic." volume="5" year="2010">Ohenoja and Ohenoja 2010</bibRefCitation>
). It is distributed from the Mediterranean area through the Temperate and Boreal zone to the Arctic and Alpine zones, being less common in the colder areas. Circumpolar, arctic-alpine, temperate, boreal and subarctic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Habitat and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Eleven collections, six of them with 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Salix glauca" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="glauca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix glauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, one with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Dryas" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Dryas octopetala" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="octopetala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Dryas octopetala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. integrifolia" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="integrifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">D. integrifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, one with 
<taxonomicName class="Eudicots" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Bistorta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Bistorta" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Bistorta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, three not reported. One record from the Rocky Mountains was also with 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. glauca" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="glauca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. glauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The soil conditions were variable. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Quel.; Mem. Soc. Emul. Montbeliard, Ser. 2, 5: 128" authorityYear="1872" baseAuthorityName="Pers." class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma mesophaeum" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="mesophaeum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma mesophaeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widespread and very versatile when it comes to hosts, including many deciduous as well as coniferous hosts (
<bibRefCitation author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
In 
<bibRefCitation author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
, it was reported that in arctic and alpine areas there is a chance of confusion with 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. marginatulum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="marginatulum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. marginatulum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, due to the fact that sometimes 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. mesophaeum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="mesophaeum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. mesophaeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, growing in such habitats, tends to have larger spores. They reported that all the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘large-spored’">'large-spored'</normalizedToken>
collections were from Iceland and Svalbard. In Greenland, we have also found collections with larger spores; indeed, nine of the eleven collections discussed here exhibited larger spores in a range from 10.3-11.7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6.4-7.1 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, a similar range to that reported for Svalbard and Iceland. At the time, 
<bibRefCitation author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
did consider creating a variety to address these collections but decided such a course of action was premature and that further study of this variation was required. With regard to the confusion with 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. marginatulum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="marginatulum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. marginatulum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the strongly bicolored cap of 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. mesophaeum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="mesophaeum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. mesophaeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should normally aid identification.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
